1 Introduction

1.1 Classification problem

In machine learning and statistics, classification is the problem of assigning a new observation to one of several predefined categories. Solution is obtained on the basis of a training set of data containing observations (or instances) whose category membership is known (supervised learning).

Denote

  • \(X\) - set of objects;
  • \(Y\) - finite set of classes;
  • \(f: X\rightarrow Y\);
  • \(L^m = {(x_1,f(x_1)),..,(x_m,f(x_m))}\) - learning sample.

Function \(f\) classifies objects correctly, but we are given only set \(L^m\). Hence we know function \(f\) only on the subset of \(X\). The goal is to find algorithm classifying all objects from \(X\).
Generalization of an âordinaryâ classification is probabilistic classification that is able to predict, given a new object, a probability distribution over a set of classes, rather than only outputting the most likely class that the object should belong to.

1.2 Classification performance evaluation: two classes

Begin with assessing binary classification quality.
Suppose that only two object types are possible \[Y = \{Y_1,Y_2\}\] A confusion matrix is a table that is often used to describe the performance of a classification model (or âclassifierâ) on a set of test data for which the true values are known.

Example.

A total of 1000 people were tested for a disease.
Out of those 1000 people, the test returned:

  • âPositiveâ results (predicting disease) 180 times,
  • âNegativeâ results (predicting no disease) 820 times.

Further tests showed that in reality 900 of tested people did not have disease \((Y_2)\) and 100 people had it \((Y_1)\).
For the 80 patients with disease test results came back positive and for other 20 diseased patients the test results were negative.

Then the corresponding confusion matrix is

confusion = data.frame('Tested negative'=c(800,20),
                       'Tested positive'=c(100,80))
rownames(confusion) <- c('No disease','Disease')
colnames(confusion)<-c("Tested negative","Tested positive")
Tested negative Tested positive
No disease 800 100
Disease 20 80

Introduce some related notations.

  • True positives (TP): These are cases in which people who tested positive had the disease.
  • True negatives (TN): These are cases in which people who tested negative did not have the disease.
  • False positives (FP): Test came back positive, but the tested person had no disease. (Also known as a âType II error.â)
  • False negatives (FN): Test came back negative, but the tested person had the disease. (Also known as a âType I error.â)

Confusion matrix is 2x2 matrix containing values TP, TN, FP, FN. The following table shows their locations in the matrix.
Row and column totals added here will be used in further calculations.

Tested negative Tested positive Row total
No disease TN = 800 FP = 100 900
Disease FN = 20 TP = 80 100
Column total 820 180

The statistics commonly calculated from confusion matrix are:

TN = confusion[1,1]
FP = confusion[1,2]
FN = confusion[2,1]
TP = confusion[2,2]
total = sum(confusion)
Disease = sum(confusion[2,]) #actualPositive
Nodisease = sum(confusion[1,])
TestedPositive = sum(confusion[,2])
TestedNegative = sum(confusion[,1])
  • Accuracy: Overall, how often is the classifier correct?
(accuracy = (TP+TN)/total)
## [1] 0.88
  • Misclassification Rate: Overall, how often is it wrong? Equivalent to 1 minus Accuracy, also known as âError Rateâ.
(misclassificationRate = (FP+FN)/total)
## [1] 0.12
  • True Positive Rate: When the person has disease, how often test result is positive? It is also known as Sensitivity or Recall.
(truePositiveRate = TP/Disease)
## [1] 0.8
  • False Positive Rate: Given that the person has no disease, how often the test result is positive?
(falsePositiveRate = FP/Nodisease)
## [1] 0.1111111
  • Specificity: Given that the person has no disease, how often the test is negative? Equivalent to 1 minus False Positive Rate.
(specificity = TN/Nodisease)
## [1] 0.8888889
  • Precision: When test is positive, how often is it correct?
# precision = 0 with no positive objects predicted
(precision = ifelse(TP==0,0,TP/TestedPositive))
## [1] 0.4444444
  • Prevalence: What is the proportion of people with the disease?
(prevalence = Disease/total)
## [1] 0.1

Compare classification performance evaluated from two confusion matrices;

\[\left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 100 & FP = 60 \\ FN = 70 & TP = 100% \end{array}% \right) \quad\ and\quad\ \left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 101 & FP = 59 \\ FN = 60 & TP = 110% \end{array}% \right) \]

It is clear that the second classifier is better: it makes fewer errors of both types with the same number of cases.

But what about this pair? \[\left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 100 & FP = 60 \\ FN = 70 & TP = 100% \end{array}% \right) \quad\ and\quad\ \left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 110 & FP = 50 \\ FN = 80 & TP = 90% \end{array}% \right) \]

There are several metrics for such comparison.
Below are few most important of them.

1.2.1 Accuracy

Accuracy defined above is often the starting point for analyzing the quality of a predictive model, as well as an obvious criterion for prediction.
It is the first characteristic the package caret shows in cross validation results.
Accuracy measures the ratio of correct predictions to the total number of cases evaluated.
It may seem obvious that the ratio of correct predictions to cases should be a key metric.
But be careful! A predictive model may have high accuracy, but be useless.

Suppose we want to detect ATM fraud during customerâs visit. Fraud in our terminology is âPositive eventâ.
It is rather rare event, so a typical confusion matrix of good classification algorithm may be

\[\left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 10000 & FP = 150 \\ FN = 50 & TP = 100% \end{array}% \right) \]

with accuracy 98.06%. Not bad!

But consider a degenerate classification algorithm that simply assigns âNegativeâ class to all visits.
Such algorithm gives confusion matrix \[\left( \begin{array}{cc} TN = 10150 & FP = 0 \\ FN = 150 & TP = 0% \end{array}% \right) \]

The accuracy of this degenerate classifier is 98.54%. The algorithm that obviously does not classify has better accuracy.

This phenomenon is called accuracy paradox.

1.2.2 Cohenâs Kappa

The second characteristic that package caret shows in cross validation results is Cohenâs Kappa.
This is essentially a measure of how well the classifier performed as compared to how well it would have performed simply by chance.

The expression for kappa is
\[ \kappa =\frac{Accuracy-Random\;Accuracy}{1-Random\;Accuracy}, \]

To define random accuracy start with general definition of accuracy \[ \begin{eqnarray*} Accuracy &=&P\left \{ No\;Disease\;\&\;Test\;is\;Negative\right\} \\ &&+P\left\{ Disease\;\&\;Test\;is\;Positive\right\} \end{eqnarray*} \]

By \(Random\;Accuracy\) we understand accuracy of a guessing classifier, for which \[P\left \{No\;Disease\;\&\;Test\;is\;Negative\right\}=P\left \{No\;Disease\right\}P\left \{Test\;is\;Negative\right\}\] \[P\left \{Disease\;\&\;Test\;is\;Positive\right\}=P\left \{Disease\right\}P\left \{Test\;is\;Positive\right\}\]

Then \[ \begin{eqnarray*} Random\;Accuracy &=&P\{No\;Disease\}P\{Test\;is\;Negative\} \\ &&+P\{Disease\}P\{Test\;is\;Positive\} \\ &=&\frac{TN+FP}{total}\frac{TN+FN}{total}+\frac{FN+TP}{total}\frac{TP+FP}{% total} \end{eqnarray*} \]

Similar to correlation coefficient, Kappa can range from -1 to +1, where 0 represents the quality that can be expected from random classifier, and 1 represents perfect predicting quality.
While kappa values below 0 are theoretically possible, Cohen notes they are unlikely in practice.
As with all correlation statistics, the kappa is a standardized and unitless value and thus has universal interpretation.

Calculate Cohenâs \(\kappa\) for the accuracy paradox confusion matrix assigning every observation to âNegativeâ.

(Skipped Code)

TN = 10150
FP = 0 
FN = 150
TP = 0
rAccuracy = ((TN+FP)*(TN+FN)+(FN+TP)*(TP+FP))/total^2
cat('Kappa = ',((TN+TP)/total - rAccuracy)/(1 - rAccuracy))
## Kappa =  0

Unlike Accuracy, Kappa estimate of degenerative classifier is quite adequate. It is the same as for random classifier.

1.2.3 F-measure

F-measure (also \(F_1\) score or F-score). The traditional F-measure (\(F_1\) score) is the harmonic mean of Precision and Recall (a.k.a. Sensitivity or True Positive Rate, see above) \[ F_{1}=\frac{2Precision\times Recall}{Precision+Recall} \]

A more general formula for a real \(\beta\) is: \[ F_{\beta }=\frac{(1+\beta ^{2}) Precision\times Recall}{\beta ^{2}Precision+Recall} \]

Increasing \(beta\) puts more emphasis on recall and vice versa. Three typical values of \(beta\) are 0.5, 1 and 2.

As any other measure F-measure is not ideal.

  • It is not sensitive to True Negatives.
  • F-measure (like Recall and Precision) is biased towards the majority of the class.

Write function F1 <- function(TN,FP,FN,TP) and calculate \(F_1\)-measure for \(F_1("Positive")\) and \(F_1("Negative")\) using the fraud confusion matrix.

(Skipped Code)

F1 <- function(TN,FP,FN,TP) {
  if(TP==0) return(0)
  precision = TP/(TP+FP)
  truePositiveRate = TP/(FN+TP)
  return(2*precision*truePositiveRate/(precision + truePositiveRate))
}
cat('Fraud is Positive event: F1 =',F1(10000,150,50,100))
## Fraud is Positive event: F1 = 0.5
cat('Fraud is Negative event: F1 =',F1(100,50,150,10000))
## Fraud is Negative event: F1 = 0.990099

1.2.4 ROC curve

ROC curve is a commonly used graph that summarizes the performance of a classifier over all possible thresholds.
It is generated by plotting the True Positive Rate (y-axis) against the False Positive Rate (x-axis) for different values of threshold for assigning observations to a given class.
AUC (Area Under Curve) is a good way to summarize ROC performance in a single number.
The origin of term âROCâ is signal processing. It is an acronym for Receiver Operating Characteristics.
ROC curve was first developed by electrical engineers and radar engineers during World War II for detecting enemy objects in battlefields and was soon introduced to psychology to account for perceptual detection of stimuli.

In the next example consider ROC curve for logistic regression classification of two two-dimensional normal samples.

library(ggplot2)
library(ROCR)
# normal distributions parameters
meanP = c(0,0)
sdP = c(2,1)
meanN = c(1,1)
sdN = c(1,2)
# sample sizes
nP = 100
nN = 300
# simulate two samples
dataROC <- data.frame(x = c(rnorm(nP,meanP[1],sdP[1]),
                            rnorm(nN,meanN[1],sdN[1])),
                       y = c(rnorm(nP,meanP[2],sdP[2]),
                             rnorm(nN,meanN[2],sdN[2])),
                       class = c('Positive',
                                 'Negative')[1+c(rep(1,nP),rep(0,nN))]) 
dataROC$class_binary<-(dataROC$class=="Positive")*1
head(dataROC)

Note that according the definitions above Sensitivity is equal to True Positive Rate and 1-Specificity is equal to False Positive Rate.

1.3 Classification performance evaluation for several classes

Let \(N\) be the number of objects to classify, \(M\) - number of classes, let also \(y_{ij}\) be 1 if object \(i\) belongs to class \(j\), and 0 otherwise.
Finally, let \(p_{ij}\) be predicted probability that object \(i\) belongs to class \(j\).
Vector \(<p_{i1},p_{i2},.,p_{i,M}>\) is the output of the classification algorithm for object \(i\).
A popular classification performance estimate is logloss.
The formula for logloss is \[ logloss=-\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\sum_{j=1}^{M}y_{ij}\ln (p_{ij}). \] For example, let the number of classes be \(M=2\) and there is only one object that needs to be classified. Then the logloss formula is \[ logloss=-y_{11}\ln (p_{11})-y_{12}\ln (p_{12}). \] If for this object the correct class is 1 then \(y_{11}=1\), \(y_{12}=0\) and \(logloss= - \ln (p_{11})\).
Suppose the ideal case when the classification algorithm returned vector \(<1,0>\). Then \(logloss=0\).
If the algorithm classifies correctly, but assigns more uncertainty to the first class: \(<0.7,0.3>\) then the penalty function is \(logloss=-\ln (0.7)\) = 0.3566749.
If predicted probability for the first class is small the penalty function can potentially go to infinity. That is why in practice input values \(p_{ij}\) are replaced by \(\max (C,p_{ij})\), where \(C\) is a small positive number.
For example, if \(C=10^{-16}\) an incorrect forecast is a subject to a penalty of 36.8413615.

Write function MultiLogLoss <- function(act, pred) for calculation of logloss using the formula above.
Argument act is a matrix \(y_{ij},~i=1,\ldots,N;~j=1,\ldots,M,\) of actual classes. Each row \(i\) should contain \(M\) elements, all of them are zeros, except for position \(t\) corresponding to the true class of observation \(i\): \(y_{it}=1\).
Argument pred is the matrix of prediction probabilities \(p_{ij}\) of the same size as \(y_{ij}\). Each row of this matrix is the vector of probabilities of observation \(i\) belonging to class \(j\).

MultiLogLoss <- function(act, pred)
{
  eps = 1e-15;
  if (!is.matrix(pred)) pred<-t(as.matrix(pred))
  if (!is.matrix(act)) act<-t(as.matrix(act))
  nr <- nrow(pred)
  pred = matrix(sapply( pred, function(x) max(eps,x)), nrow = nr)      
  pred = matrix(sapply( pred, function(x) min(1-eps,x)), nrow = nr)
  #normalize rows
  ll = sum(act*log(sweep(pred, 1, rowSums(pred), FUN="/")))
  ll = -ll/nrow(act)
  return(ll);
}

Check the logloss function for the following examples.

2 Recursive Partitioning Using the RPART Package

2.1 Example: Manual implementation of Gini impurity measure

To understand Gini impurity measure create a simple vector containing 2 classes:

Create predictor and data frame.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
ClassesTest<-c(0,1,1,0,1)
PredictorsTest<-c(1,2,3,4,5)
TestData<-as.data.frame(cbind(PredictorsTest,ClassesTest))
plot(TestData)

Run classification tree algorithm.

testTree<-rpart(ClassesTest~PredictorsTest, data=TestData,
              control = rpart.control(cp = 0.00,minbucket=1,minsplit=2),method="class")
printcp(testTree)
## 
## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = ClassesTest ~ PredictorsTest, data = TestData, 
##     method = "class", control = rpart.control(cp = 0, minbucket = 1, 
##         minsplit = 2))
## 
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] PredictorsTest
## 
## Root node error: 2/5 = 0.4
## 
## n= 5 
## 
##     CP nsplit rel error xerror    xstd
## 1 0.50      0       1.0    2.5 0.00000
## 2 0.25      1       0.5    1.5 0.54772
## 3 0.00      3       0.0    2.0 0.44721

The table shows the splits, the cost function for complexity of the tree cp and the two errors: before and after cross validation.

Visualize the tree.

prp(testTree,extra=4, # display prob of classes in the node
    branch=.5, # change angle of branch lines
    shadow.col="gray", # shadows under the leaves
    branch.lty=3, # draw branches using dotted lines
    split.cex=1.2, # make the split text larger than the node text
    split.prefix="is ", # put "is " before split text
    split.suffix="?", # put "?" after split text
    split.box.col="lightgray", # lightgray split boxes (default is white)
    split.border.col="darkgray", # darkgray border on split boxes
    split.round=.5)

Parameter extra=4 shows class predicted by the leaf and probabilities of classes (total is 1).

The CP-table shows that the tree can be pruned: xerror is up in the last row.
Find the best CP level.

(best.CP = testTree$cptable[which.min(testTree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"])
## [1] 0.25

Prune the tree to the best CP level.

prunedTree <- prune(testTree, cp = best.CP)
printcp(prunedTree)
##

## 2 0.25      1       0.5    1.5 0.54772

Show the tree

    branch=.5, # change angle of branch lines

Check how Gini impurity measure makes decisions about branching the tree at each step.

Simplify the task by assigning lower values of the predictor to the first class and higher values to the second class.

Now do the same classification using tree.

Note that mclust did clustering: the method did not use training sample like rpart does.
Of course, in exchange mclust knows about the model assumption: normal mixed model.

Prepare the data for rpart and grow the tree.

colnames(mixModelSample)<-c("X","Y")
mixModelSample<-as.data.frame(mixModelSample)
myMixTest<-rpart(Y~X, data=mixModelSample,
              control = rpart.control(cp = 0.00,minbucket=1,minsplit=2),method="class")
printcp(myMixTest)

2.3.2 Creating and Plotting Small Classification Tree

Create formula for the tree.

(formula = formula(paste(classColName,'.',sep='~')))

In the following call we use one control parameter: minbucket - the minimum number of observations in any terminal node.

set.seed(9)

The table in the output shows the summary of the fitted tree.
Rows correspond to different sizes of the tree.
The table has the following columns:

  • CP shows complexity parameter controlling the tree size
  • nsplit - number of splitting nodes in the tree
  • rel error - the error of the training set relative to the error with no splits
  • xerror - the relative error of the test set calculated with k-fold cross validation (by default k=10)
  • xstd - standard deviation of xerror

Plot cross validation x-error versus tree size (and complexity parameter).

plotcp(smallTree)

The horizontal dotted line shows the level of 1 standard error xstd above the minimum of xerror.
To prune the tree select the level of cp corresponding to the first point from the left below the standard error line.

Another way of selecting the parameter cp is:

(best.CP = 
   smallTree$cptable[which.min(smallTree$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"])
## [1] 0.00174992

Both plotcp() and best.CP show that we can prune smallTree reducing the number of splits in it.

Visualize the tree using prp().

    split.border.col="darkgray", # darkgray border on split boxes
    split.round=.5)

0 numbers in each leaf box display estimated class probabilities in this node. Maximum probability corresponds to the estimated class number.

Function prune() returns new rpart object that is trimmed to the value of optimal CP.

prunedTree <- prune(smallTree, cp = best.CP)

3 Trees vs.Â Linear Models

Compare work of tree model and linear logistic regression model as binary classification methods. Logistic regression partitions feature space by one hyper plane.
Obtained semispaces define the two classes.
Classification tree algorithm recursively partitions feature space by a hyper planes orthogonal to one of the axes. So, the resulting critical domain can be much more complex than semispace.

Consider the following two examples.

3.1 Example. Galtonâs data

Galtonâs data on the heights of parents and their children can be found in package HistData.
This data set lists the individual observations for 934 children in 205 families on which Galton (1886) based his cross-tabulation.

library(HistData)
data(GaltonFamilies)

Families are largely listed in descending order of fathers and mothers height.

Reshuffle them to ensure correct cross validation procedure.

set.seed(0)
GaltonFamilies = GaltonFamilies[sample(nrow(GaltonFamilies)),]
str(GaltonFamilies)
## 'data.frame':    934 obs. of  8 variables:
##  $ family         : Factor w/ 205 levels "001","002","003",..: 92 182 148 35 204 115 107 72 68 49 ...
##  $ father         : num  70 66.5 68.5 71 62 69 69 70 70.5 71.5 ...
##  $ mother         : num  61 62.5 63.5 69 66 63.5 66 65 65 64.5 ...
##  $ midparentHeight: num  67.9 67 68.5 72.8 66.6 ...
##  $ children       : int  2 7 1 5 3 7 9 7 5 7 ...
##  $ childNum       : int  2 5 1 2 1 3 3 7 2 5 ...
##  $ gender         : Factor w/ 2 levels "female","male": 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 1 1 1 ...
##  $ childHeight    : num  67 62.5 68.2 74 64 66 69 62 65 64.5 ...

Note that mid-parent height is calculated as
midparentHeight = (father + 1.08*mother)/2
The goal is to identify each child gender by her or his height and mid-parent height.
Look at the data scatterplot.

Gender = as.character(GaltonFamilies$gender)=="female"
plot(GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight[Gender],GaltonFamilies$childHeight[Gender],type="p",pch=16,col="red",
     ylim=c(min(GaltonFamilies$childHeight),max(GaltonFamilies$childHeight)),ylab="Child Height",xlab="Parent Height")
points(GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight[!Gender],GaltonFamilies$childHeight[!Gender],type="p",pch=16,col="blue")

Apply Logistic Regression to the data.

modelFormula = formula('gender ~ midparentHeight + childHeight')
logrFit <- glm(modelFormula, family=binomial("logit"),data=GaltonFamilies)
beta = as.numeric(logrFit$coefficients)
beta
## [1] -18.7653673  -0.7668881   1.0802791

The equation of the line, separating target classes is \[ f(x)=-(\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x)/\beta _{2} \]

Draw it on the plot above.

f.x <-  -(beta[1]+beta[2]*GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight)/beta[3]
plot(GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight[Gender],GaltonFamilies$childHeight[Gender],type="p",pch=16,col="red",
     ylim=c(min(GaltonFamilies$childHeight),max(GaltonFamilies$childHeight)),ylab="Child Height",xlab="Parent Height")
points(GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight[!Gender],GaltonFamilies$childHeight[!Gender],type="p",pch=16,col="blue")
lines(GaltonFamilies$midparentHeight,f.x,col="black")

We see that in spite of high noise level straight line successfully separates male and female items.

Let us check the predictive quality of the method with 10-fold cross validation implemented in the caret package.

library(caret)
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
logrTrain <- train(modelFormula,data=GaltonFamilies,
                   method = 'glm', trControl = ctrl)

3.2 Example. Rectangular class domain

Simulate the data with rectangular shapes of classes.
Each observation is three-dimensional vector with two numeric features and one categorical (type) with possible values âPositiveâ or âNegativeâ.
The goal is to identify type on the basis of first two features.

N = 1000
xPos = 0.2
yMinPos = 0.2
yMaxPos = 0.7
newData = data.frame(x=runif(N),y=runif(N))
newData$type = with(newData,ifelse(x>xPos & y>yMinPos & y<yMaxPos,
                        'Positive','Negative'))

Add some noise at the beginning of the data and reshuffle.

n = N/10
newData$type[1:n] = c('Positive','Negative')[1+rbinom(n, 1, 0.5)]
newData = newData[sample(nrow(newData)),]

Plot the data
